 shows in this study of the novelist's life and work, Cather's sexual coming-of-age occurred at a time when a cultural transition was recasting love between women as sexual deviance rather than romantic friendship. At the same time, the very identity of "America" was characterized by great instability as the United States emerged as a modern industrial nation and imperial power. Indeed, both terms, "queer" and "America," achieved fresh ideological potency at the turn of the century. Willa Cather: Queering America is an enlightening unpacking of Cather's writings, from her controversial love letters of the 1890s--in which "queer" is employed to denote sexual deviance--to her epic novels, short stories, and critical writings. Lindemann points to the "queer" qualities of Cather's fiction--rebellion against traditional fictional form, with sometimes unlikable characters, lack of emphasis on heroic action, and lack of engagement in the drama of heterosexual desire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aFeminism and literaturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aHomosexuality and literaturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aLesbianszUnited StatesxIntellectual life. 0aLove-lettersxHistory. 0aSexual orientation in literature. 0aWomen and literaturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Archive 1898-1999 (pre Pub)z978311044248940uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/lind11324423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231500272.jpg  a978-3-11-044248-9  CUP eBook Package Archive 1898-1999 (pre Pub)c1898d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aP